			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: LDoN song lineup<a name="24108"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Feb 26 04 1:31 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Edit: For the record, I (almost) NEVER twist manasong during combat. I won't change my attitude on that until someone conclusively proves to me that the few points of mana that will be regenerated in the course of a 45-60 second fight actually makes any difference. Any caster that complains can gate. I've been known to throw in a few pulses of it across long drawn out fights, but it is a rule of thumb that my bard runs manasong during downtime only.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
I was pretty much the same way all the time before POP.  I totally agree with the logic.  Chorus/Wind of Marr, however, generates 21 mana per tick -- over 200 per minute -- and in battles that average one to two minutes long, giving every caster in range of Chorus an extra 200 mana a minute suddenly seems like a good idea.  Plus, the HP regen when you are fighting AE or rampage mobs can save a bit of healing mana.  So with Chorus of Marr (and to a lesser extent Chorus of Replenishment at 58) where you are effecting a great many people, it begins to start looking like a smarter move.
<br />

<br />
To everyone evaluating mana songs, remember -- the instrument modifier does NOT change the amount of mana generated.  Chorus of Clarity used to be the exception, but when they changed it to an icon-producing song, Voice modifiers stopped increasing the amount of mana it generates.  I am not sure if Amp still affects it or not or whether that's been tested.  But when they nerfed the song, they dramatically changed how it works.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
